==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Limp
<hw>Limp</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A manner of walking in which the
movement of one or both legs is noticeably abnormal, usually due to
injury or disease; a halt; the act of limping.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Limp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Limp
<hw>Limp</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Ore Washing)</fld> <def>A scraper for
removing poor ore or refuse from the sieve.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Limp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Limp
<hw>Limp</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Icel. <ets>limpa</ets> limpness,
weakness, and E. <ets>lap</ets>, <pos>n.</pos>, <ets>lop</ets>, <pos>v.
t.</pos> Cf. <er>Limber</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Flaccid; flabby, as flesh.</def> <rj><au>Walton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Lacking stiffness; flimsy; <as>as, a <ex>limp</ex>
cravat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

